<div class="jumbotron jumbotron-news-landing">
  <div class="container container-padded container-fluid">
    <div class="pfda-cards pfda-cards-align-centered pfda-cards-stretch">
      <div class="pfda-card pfda-challenge-card pfda-card-default pfda-card-rounded pfda-card-bordered pfda-card-padded pfda-card-shadow">
        <div class="media">
          <div class="pfda-challenge-diagram">
            <%= image_tag("challenges/TMB_challenge_graphic.png", class: "img-responsive center-block", alt: "TMB Challenge graphic") %>
          </div>
          <div class="media-body pfda-padded">
            <div class="pfda-card-body text-justify">
              <div>
                Tumor Mutational Burden (TMB) is an important biomarker for development of immunotherapy drugs and clinical decision making in their use. There are a large and growing number of diagnostic devices with a TMB readout. However, a major limitation in the clinical use of TMB has been the lack of standardization in the calculation and reporting of TMB values.
              </div>
              <br>
              <div>
                The Friends of Cancer Research (FOCR) has organized a <%= link_to "working group", "https://friendsofcancerresearch.org/tmb", target: "_blank" %> of industry and government stakeholders to develop guidance for TMB calculation and reporting. To help validate and refine the emerging standards, and to encourage further development of methods for clinical diagnostic pipelines that report TMB, FOCR and precisionFDA are hosting a Tumor Mutational Burden Challenge.
              </div>
              <br>
              <div>
                Using the novel and not-yet-published sequencing data generated by the TMB working group, Challenge participants will apply new or existing methods for somatic variant calling, germline and somatic variant discrimination from tumor-only sequencing, TMB calculation, and prediction of whole-exome TMB values from panel sequencing data. The Challenge is divided into two Phases:
                <br>
                <ul>
                  <li>
                    Somatic variant calling: participants will identify variants in whole-exome tumor data, and optionally classify variants as germline or somatic.
                  </li>
                  <li>
                    TMB estimation: participants will have access to variant calls from tumor panel sequencing and whole-exome TMB scores for a set of training samples during a short algorithm training period, followed by a longer validation period in which they apply their algorithm to tumor panel sequencing from an unrelated set of samples.
                  </li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <br>
              <div>
                The dates for these Phases are as follows:
                <br>
                <div>
                  Phase 1: Somatic Variant Calling: June 21 - July 18
                </div>
                <div>
                  Phase 2: TMB Estimation:
                </div>
                <ul style="list-style: none;">
                  <li>Training: July 19 - Aug 8</li><li>Validation: Aug 9 - Sept 12</li>
                </ul>
              </div>
              <br>
              <div>
                Participants may submit results for either or both Phases. Submissions will be evaluated and awards given based on a number of different metrics. Finally, there will be a Community Phase during which Challenge participants will be invited to collaborate on developing best-practices that will be shared with the working group and the larger community.
              </div>
              <br>
              <div>
                You are encouraged to participate in this challenge to help improve the utility of TMB as a clinical biomarker.
              </div>
              <br>
              <div>
                <i>*Please note: any individuals or organizations involved in the FOCR working group at any time are not eligible to participate in this challenge.</i>
              </div>
              <br>
              <p><%= link_to "Click here to sign up for more information", "https://www.surveymonkey.com/r/YL5JHQH", class: "btn btn-primary", target: "_blank" %></p>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</div>
